{
  "text": "On the other hand, when f (t) satisfies a finitary version of (1.8), then we obtain a corresponding finite asymptotic approximation result in Theorem 2.6. More specifically, if the right-hand side of (1.8) is a finite sum, then we show that the corresponding solution, u(t), admits a finite sum approximation of the same type analogous to (1.6). Theorem 2.6 is also suitable for the case when the force is not smooth, but belongs only to a pre-specified Sobolev class. Theorem 1.2 develops one of the possible avenues of extending the Foias-Saut theory [CITATION_1] for the NSE to the non-potential force case. The finite sum version, Theorem 2.6, which is a new feature only for the non-potential force case, allows asymptotic analysis of the solution even when the force has restricted regularity and only limited information on the force's asymptotic behavior is known. Our analysis, moreover, explicitly indicates how each term in the expansion of the force integrates into the expansion of the solution. We emphasize that the assumptions that we do impose on the force are very natural. This point is not so obvious because if one directly adopts the argument of Foias-Saut in [CITATION_2] , one would then be led to impose conditions on time-derivatives of all orders on the force. We, nevertheless, are able to avoid these conditions and ultimately establish the claimed expansion by applying the refined approach, in the case of periodic domains, initiated in [CITATION_3] . We also remark that we obtain a welcome technical improvement over [CITATION_4] in obtaining the expansion in Sobolev spaces, when Gevrey regularity is not available; it requires a more elaborate bootstrapping process which is carried out in Part II of the proof of Proposition 3.4.",
